[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] It is often used together with **constant propagation**, which substitutes variables whose values are known to be constant.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] An advanced form of constant propagation known as sparse conditional constant propagation can more accurately propagate constants and simultaneously remove dead code.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant folding is the process of recognizing and evaluating constant expressions at compile time rather than computing them at runtime.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Terms in constant expressions are typically simple literals, such as the integer literal `2`, but they may also be variables whose values are known at compile time.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Most compilers would not actually generate two multiply instructions and a store for this statement.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Instead, they identify constructs such as these and substitute the computed values at compile time (in this case, `2,048,000`).
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant folding can make use of arithmetic identities.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] If `x` is numeric, the value of `0 * x` is zero even if the compiler does not know the value of `x`.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant folding may apply to more than just numbers.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Concatenation of string literals and constant strings can be constant folded.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Code such as `"abc" + "def"` may be replaced with `"abcdef"`.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Cross compilers have to ensure that the behaviour of the arithmetic operations on the host architecture matches that on the target architecture, as otherwise enabling constant folding will change the behaviour of the program.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] This is of particular importance in the case of floating point operations, whose precise implementation may vary widely.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant propagation is the process of substituting the values of known constants in expressions at compile time.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Such constants include those defined above, as well as intrinsic functions applied to constant values.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant propagation is implemented in compilers using reaching definition analysis results.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] If all a variable's reaching definitions are the same assignment - which assigns a same constant to the variable - then the variable will always have the same value, and can be replaced with the constant.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant propagation can also cause conditional branches to simplify to one or more unconditional statements, if the conditional expression can be evaluated to true or false at compile time to determine the only possible outcome.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Constant folding and propagation are typically used together to achieve many simplifications and reductions, and their interleaved, iterative application continues until those effects cease.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] Traditional constant propagation produces no further optimization; it does not restructure programs.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] However, a similar optimization, sparse conditional constant propagation, goes further by selecting the appropriate conditional branch, and removing the always-true conditional test.
[src:static-single-assignment/constant-folding] If that pseudocode constitutes a function body, the compiler knows the function evaluates to integer constant `4`, allowing replacement of calls to the function with `4`, and further increasing program efficiency.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] In compiler theory, **dead-code elimination** (**DCE**, **dead-code removal**, **dead-code stripping**, or **dead-code strip**) is a compiler optimization to remove dead code (code that does not affect the program results).
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Removing such code has several benefits: it shrinks program size (an important consideration in some contexts); reduces resource usage, such as the number of bytes to be transferred; and allows the running program to avoid executing irrelevant operations, which reduces its running time.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] It can also enable further optimizations by simplifying program structure.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Dead code includes code that can never be executed (unreachable code) and code that only affects dead variables (written to, but never read again), that is, irrelevant to the program.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Consider the following example written in C.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Simple analysis of the uses of values would show that the value of `b` after the first assignment is not used inside `foo`.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, `b` is declared as a local variable inside `foo`, so its value cannot be used outside `foo`.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Thus, the variable `b` is *dead* and an optimizer can reclaim its storage space and eliminate its initialization.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, because the first return statement is executed unconditionally and there is no label after it which a "goto" could reach, no feasible execution path reaches the second assignment to `b`.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Thus, the assignment is *unreachable* and can be removed.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] If the procedure had a more complex control flow, such as a label after the return statement and a `goto` elsewhere in the procedure, then a feasible execution path might exist to the assignment to `b`.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Also, even though some calculations are performed in the function, their values are not stored in locations accessible outside the scope of this function.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, given the function returns a static value (96), it may be simplified to the value it returns (this simplification is called constant folding).
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Most advanced compilers have options to activate dead-code elimination, sometimes at varying levels.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] A lower level might only remove instructions that cannot be executed.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] A higher level might also not reserve space for unused variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] A yet higher level might determine instructions or functions that serve no purpose and eliminate them.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] A common use of dead-code elimination is as an alternative to optional code inclusion via a preprocessor.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Because the constant `DEBUG_MODE` will always evaluate to false (due to being defined as so), the code inside the if statement can never be executed, and dead-code elimination would remove it entirely from the optimized program.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] This technique is common in debugging to optionally activate blocks of code; using an optimizer with dead-code elimination eliminates the need for using a preprocessor to perform the same task.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] In practice, much of the dead code that an optimizer finds is created by other transformations in the optimizer.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] For example, the classic techniques for operator strength reduction insert new computations into the code and render the older, more expensive computations dead.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Subsequent dead-code elimination removes those calculations and completes the effect (without complicating the strength-reduction algorithm).
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Historically, dead-code elimination was performed using information derived from data-flow analysis.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] An algorithm based on static single-assignment form (SSA) appears in the original journal article on *SSA* form by Ron Cytron et al.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Robert Shillingsburg (aka Shillner) improved on the algorithm and developed a companion algorithm for removing useless control-flow operations.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Dead code is normally considered dead *unconditionally*.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Therefore, it is reasonable attempting to remove dead code through dead-code elimination at compile time.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] However, in practice it is also common for code sections to represent dead or unreachable code only *under certain conditions*, which may not be known at the time of compilation or assembly.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Also, the software (for example, a driver or resident service) may be configurable to include or exclude certain features depending on user preferences, rendering unused code portions useless in a particular scenario.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] The techniques used to dynamically detect demand, identify and resolve dependencies, remove such conditionally dead code, and to recombine the remaining code at load or runtime are called **dynamic dead-code elimination** or **dynamic dead-instruction elimination**.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] However, language implementations doing just-in-time compilation may dynamically optimize for dead-code elimination.
[src:static-single-assignment/dead-code-elimination] Although with a rather different focus, similar approaches are sometimes also utilized for dynamic software updating and hot patching.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] In computer science, a node d of a control-flow graph **dominates** a node n if every path from the *entry node* to n must go through d.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Notationally, this is written as *d* dom *n* (or sometimes *d* ≫ *n*).
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] By definition, every node dominates itself.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Dominance was first introduced by Reese T.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Prosser in a 1959 paper on analysis of flow diagrams.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Prosser did not present an algorithm for computing dominance, which had to wait ten years for Edward S.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Ron Cytron *et al.* rekindled interest in dominance in 1989 when they applied it to the problem of efficiently computing the placement of φ functions, which are used in static single assignment form.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Dominators, and dominance frontiers particularly, have applications in compilers for computing static single assignment form.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] A number of compiler optimizations can also benefit from dominators.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] The flow graph in this case comprises basic blocks.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Dominators play a crucial role in control flow analysis by identifying the program behaviors that are relevant to a specific statement or operation, which helps in optimizing and simplifying the control flow of programs for analysis.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Automatic parallelization benefits from postdominance frontiers.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] This is an efficient method of computing control dependence, which is critical to the analysis.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Memory usage analysis can benefit from the dominator tree to easily find leaks and identify high memory usage.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] In hardware systems, dominators are used for computing signal probabilities for test generation, estimating switching activities for power and noise analysis, and selecting cut points in equivalence checking.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] In software systems, they are used for reducing the size of the test set in structural testing techniques such as statement and branch coverage.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Let $n_{0}$ be the source node on the Control-flow graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] The dominator of the start node is the start node itself.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] The set of dominators for any other node n is the intersection of the set of dominators for all predecessors p of n .
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] The node n is also in the set of dominators for n .
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] The direct solution is quadratic in the number of nodes, or O(*n*2).
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Lengauer and Tarjan developed an algorithm which is almost linear, and in practice, except for a few artificial graphs, the algorithm and a simplified version of it are as fast or faster than any other known algorithm for graphs of all sizes and its advantage increases with graph size.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Harvey, and Ken Kennedy of Rice University describe an algorithm that essentially solves the above data flow equations but uses well engineered data structures to improve performance.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Analogous to the definition of dominance above, a node *z* is said to **post-dominate** a node *n* if all paths to the exit node of the graph starting at *n* must go through *z*.
[src:static-single-assignment/dominator-graph-theory] Similarly, the **immediate post-dominator** of a node *n* is the postdominator of *n* that doesn't strictly postdominate any other strict postdominators of *n*.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate representation** (**IR**) is the data structure or code used internally by a compiler or virtual machine to represent source code.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] An IR is designed to be conducive to further processing, such as optimization and translation.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] A "good" IR must be *accurate* – capable of representing the source code without loss of information – and *independent* of any particular source or target language.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] An IR may take one of several forms: an in-memory data structure, or a special tuple- or stack-based code readable by the program.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] In the latter case it is also called an *intermediate language*.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] A canonical example is found in most modern compilers.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] For example, the CPython interpreter transforms the linear human-readable text representing a program into an intermediate graph structure that allows flow analysis and re-arrangement before execution.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Use of an intermediate representation such as this allows compiler systems like the GNU Compiler Collection and LLVM to be used by many different source languages to generate code for many different target architectures.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate language** is the language of an abstract machine designed to aid in the analysis of computer programs.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] The term comes from their use in compilers, where the source code of a program is translated into a form more suitable for code-improving transformations before being used to generate object or machine code for a target machine.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] A popular format for intermediate languages is three-address code.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] The term is also used to refer to languages used as intermediates by some high-level programming languages which do not output object or machine code themselves, but output the intermediate language only.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] This intermediate language is submitted to a compiler for such language, which then outputs finished object or machine code.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] This is usually done to ease the process of optimization or to increase portability by using an intermediate language that has compilers for many processors and operating systems, such as C.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Languages used for this fall in complexity between high-level languages and low-level languages, such as assembly languages.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Variants of C have been designed to provide C's features as a portable assembly language, including C-- and the C Intermediate Language.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] The GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) uses several intermediate languages internally to simplify portability and cross-compilation.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] The LLVM compiler framework is based on the LLVM IR intermediate language, of which the compact, binary serialized representation is also referred to as "bitcode" and has been productized by Apple.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Like GIMPLE Bytecode, LLVM Bitcode is useful in link-time optimization.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Like GCC, LLVM also targets some IRs meant for direct distribution, including Google's PNaCl IR and SPIR.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] A further development within LLVM is the use of *Multi-Level Intermediate Representation* (MLIR) with the potential to generate code for different heterogeneous targets, and to combine the outputs of different compilers.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] The ILOC intermediate language is used in classes on compiler design as a simple target language.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] Static analysis tools often use an intermediate representation.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] For instance, Radare2 is a toolbox for binary files analysis and reverse-engineering.
[src:static-single-assignment/intermediate-representation] It uses the intermediate languages ESIL and REIL to analyze binary files.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In compiler optimization, **register allocation** is the process of assigning local automatic variables and expression results to a limited number of processor registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation can happen over a basic block (*local register allocation*), over a whole function/procedure (*global register allocation*), or across function boundaries traversed via call-graph (*interprocedural register allocation*).
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] When done per function/procedure the calling convention may require insertion of save/restore around each call-site.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In many programming languages, the programmer may use any number of variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The computer can quickly read and write registers in the CPU, so the computer program runs faster when more variables can be in the CPU's registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Also, sometimes code accessing registers is more compact, so the code is smaller, and can be fetched faster if it uses registers rather than memory.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] However, the number of registers is limited.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Therefore, when the compiler is translating code to machine-language, it must decide how to allocate variables to the limited number of registers in the CPU.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Not all variables are in use (or "live") at the same time, so, over the lifetime of a program, a given register may be used to hold different variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] However, two variables in use at the *same* time cannot be assigned to the same register without corrupting one of the variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] If there are not enough registers to hold all the variables, some variables may be moved to and from RAM.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This process is called "spilling" the registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Over the lifetime of a program, a variable can be both spilled and stored in registers: this variable is then considered as "split".
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Accessing RAM is significantly slower than accessing registers and so a compiled program runs slower.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Therefore, an optimizing compiler aims to assign as many variables to registers as possible.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] A high "Register pressure" is a technical term that means that more spills and reloads are needed; it is defined by Braun et al. as "the number of simultaneously live variables at an instruction".
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In addition, some computer designs cache frequently-accessed registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] So, programs can be further optimized by assigning the same register to a source and destination of a `move` instruction whenever possible.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This is especially important if the compiler is using an intermediate representation such as static single-assignment form (SSA).
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In particular, when SSA is not fully optimized it can artificially generate additional `move` instructions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation consists therefore of choosing where to store the variables at runtime, i.e. inside or outside registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] If the variable is to be stored in registers, then the allocator needs to determine in which register(s) this variable will be stored.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Eventually, another challenge is to determine the duration for which a variable should stay at the same location.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] A register allocator, disregarding the chosen allocation strategy, can rely on a set of core actions to address these challenges.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This action consists of increasing the number of move instructions between registers, i.e. make a variable live in different registers during its lifetime, instead of one.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This occurs in the split live range approach.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This action consists of assigning a register to a variable.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This action consists of limiting the number of moves between registers, thus limiting the total number of instructions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] For instance, by identifying a variable live across different methods, and storing it into one register during its whole lifetime.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Many register allocation approaches optimize for one or more specific categories of actions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation raises several problems that can be tackled (or avoided) by different register allocation approaches.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In some architectures, assigning a value to one register can affect the value of another: this is called aliasing.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] architecture has four general purpose 32-bit registers that can also be used as 16-bit or 8-bit registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In this case, assigning a 32-bit value to the eax register will affect the value of the al register.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This problem is an act to force some variables to be assigned to particular registers.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] , parameters are commonly passed in R3-R10 and the return value is passed in R3.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This NP-completeness is entirely dependent upon exactly how the problem is structured.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] portion of the register allocation problem can be solved in linear time.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] What causes the general graph coloring problem to be NP-complete and what causes the some versions of the register allocation problem to be NP-complete are distinct.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation can happen over a basic block of code: it is said to be "local", and was first mentioned by Horwitz et al.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] As basic blocks do not contain branches, the allocation process is thought to be fast, because the management of control-flow graph merge points in register allocation reveals itself a time-consuming operation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] However, this approach is thought not to produce as optimized code as the "global" approach, which operates over the whole compilation unit (a method or procedure for instance).
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Graph-coloring allocation is the predominant approach to solve register allocation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In this approach, nodes in the graph represent live ranges (variables, temporaries, virtual/symbolic registers) that are candidates for register allocation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Edges connect live ranges that interfere, i.e., live ranges that are simultaneously live at at least one program point.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation then reduces to the graph coloring problem in which colors (registers) are assigned to the nodes such that two nodes connected by an edge do not receive the same color.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Using liveness analysis, an interference graph can be built.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The interference graph, which is an Interval graph where the nodes are the program's variables, is used to model which variables cannot be allocated to the same register.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] **Build**: build the interference graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] **Coalesce**: merge the live ranges of non-interfering variables related by copy instructions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] **Spill cost**: compute the spill cost of each variable.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This assesses the impact of mapping a variable to memory on the speed of the final program.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] **Spill Code**: insert spill instructions, i.e. loads and stores to commute values between registers and memory.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] **Select**: assign a register to each variable.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The graph-coloring allocation has three major drawbacks.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] First, it relies on graph-coloring, which is an NP-complete problem, to decide which variables are spilled.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Although finding a minimal coloring for general graphs is indeed an NP-complete problem, minimal coloring of Interval graphs (including interference graphs) can be done in linear time (see Linear scan below); Therefore, this technique does not full utilize the problem's assumptions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Second, unless live-range splitting is used, evicted variables are spilled everywhere: store instructions are inserted as early as possible, i.e., just after variable definitions; load instructions are respectively inserted late, just before variable use.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Third, a variable that is not spilled is kept in the same register throughout its whole lifetime.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] On the other hand, a single register name may appear in multiple register classes, where a class is a set of register names that are interchangeable in a particular role.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Then, multiple register names may be aliases for a single hardware register.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Finally, graph coloring is an aggressive technique for allocating registers, but is computationally expensive due to its use of the interference graph, which can have a worst-case size that is quadratic in the number of live ranges.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The traditional formulation of graph-coloring register allocation implicitly assumes a single bank of non-overlapping general-purpose registers and does not handle irregular architectural features like overlapping registers pairs, special purpose registers and multiple register banks.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] One later improvement of Chaitin-style graph-coloring approach was found by Briggs et al.: it is called conservative coalescing.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This improvement adds a criterion to decide when two live ranges can be merged.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Mainly, in addition to the non-interfering requirements, two variables can only be coalesced if their merging will not cause further spilling.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Briggs et al. introduces a second improvement to Chaitin's works which is biased coloring.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Biased coloring tries to assign the same color in the graph-coloring to live range that are copy related.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Linear scan is another global register allocation approach.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It was first proposed by Poletto et al. in 1999.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In this approach, the code is not turned into a graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Instead, all the variables are linearly scanned to determine their live range, represented as an interval.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Once the live ranges of all variables have been figured out, the intervals are traversed chronologically.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Although this traversal could help identifying variables whose live ranges interfere, no interference graph is being built and the variables are allocated in a greedy way.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The motivation for this approach is speed; not in terms of execution time of the generated code, but in terms of time spent in code generation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Typically, the standard graph coloring approaches produce quality code, but have a significant overhead, the used graph coloring algorithm having a quadratic cost.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Owing to this feature, linear scan is the approach currently used in several JIT compilers, like the Hotspot client compiler, V8, Jikes RVM, and the Android Runtime (ART).
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The Hotspot server compiler uses graph coloring for its superior code.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] However, the linear scan presents two major drawbacks.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] First, due to its greedy aspect, it does not take lifetime holes into account, i.e.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] "ranges where the value of the variable is not needed".
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Besides, a spilled variable will stay spilled for its entire lifetime.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Many other research works followed up on the Poletto's linear scan algorithm.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Traub et al., for instance, proposed an algorithm called second-chance binpacking aiming at generating code of better quality.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In this approach, spilled variables get the opportunity to be stored later in a register by using a different heuristic from the one used in the standard linear scan algorithm.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Instead of using live intervals, the algorithm relies on live ranges, meaning that if a range needs to be spilled, it is not necessary to spill all the other ranges corresponding to this variable.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Linear scan allocation was also adapted to take advantage from the SSA form: the properties of this intermediate representation simplify the allocation algorithm and allow lifetime holes to be computed directly.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] First, the time spent in data-flow graph analysis, aimed at building the lifetime intervals, is reduced, namely because variables are unique.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It consequently produces shorter live intervals, because each new assignment corresponds to a new live interval.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] To avoid modeling intervals and liveness holes, Rogers showed a simplification called future-active sets that successfully removed intervals for 80% of instructions.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In the context of register allocation, coalescing is the act of merging variable-to-variable move operations by allocating those two variables to the same location.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The coalescing operation takes place after the interference graph is built.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Once two nodes have been coalesced, they must get the same color and be allocated to the same register, once the copy operation becomes unnecessary.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Doing coalescing might have both positive and negative impacts on the colorability of the interference graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] For example, one negative impact that coalescing could have on graph inference colorability is when two nodes are coalesced, as the result node will have a union of the edges of those being coalesced.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] A positive impact of coalescing on inference graph colorability is, for example, when a node interferes with both nodes being coalesced, the degree of the node is reduced by one which leads to improving the overall colorability of the interference graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It was first introduced in Chaitin's original register allocator.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This heuristic aims at coalescing any non-interfering, copy-related nodes.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] From the perspective of copy elimination, this heuristic has the best results.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] On the other hand, aggressive coalescing could impact the colorability of the inference graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It mainly uses the same heuristic as aggressive coalescing but it merges moves if, and only if, it does not compromise the colorability of the interference graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It removes one particular move at the time, while keeping the colorability of the graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It is based on aggressive coalescing, but if the inference graph colorability is compromised, then it gives up as few moves as possible.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Some other register allocation approaches do not limit to one technique to optimize register's use.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Cavazos et al., for instance, proposed a solution where it is possible to use both the linear scan and the graph coloring algorithms.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In this approach, the choice between one or the other solution is determined dynamically: first, a machine learning algorithm is used "offline", that is to say not at runtime, to build a heuristic function that determines which allocation algorithm needs to be used.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The heuristic function is then used at runtime; in light of the code behavior, the allocator can then choose between one of the two available algorithms.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Trace register allocation is a recent approach developed by Eisl et al.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This technique handles the allocation locally: it relies on dynamic profiling data to determine which branches will be the most frequently used in a given control flow graph.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] It then infers a set of "traces" (i.e. code segments) in which the merge point is ignored in favor of the most used branch.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Each trace is then independently processed by the allocator.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] This approach can be considered as hybrid because it is possible to use different register allocation algorithms between the different traces.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Split allocation is another register allocation technique that combines different approaches, usually considered as opposite.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] For instance, the hybrid allocation technique can be considered as split because the first heuristic building stage is performed offline, and the heuristic use is performed online.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Diouf et al. proposed an allocation technique relying both on offline and online behaviors, namely static and dynamic compilation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] During the offline stage, an optimal spill set is first gathered using Integer Linear Programming.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Then, live ranges are annotated using the `compressAnnotation` algorithm which relies on the previously identified optimal spill set.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation is performed afterwards during the online stage, based on the data collected in the offline phase.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] In 2007, Bouchez et al. suggested as well to split the register allocation in different stages, having one stage dedicated to spilling, and one dedicated to coloring and coalescing.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Several metrics have been used to assess the performance of one register allocation technique against the other.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Register allocation has typically to deal with a trade-off between code quality, i.e. code that executes quickly, and analysis overhead, i.e. the time spent determining analyzing the source code to generate code with optimized register allocation.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] From this perspective, execution time of the generated code and time spent in liveness analysis are relevant metrics to compare the different techniques.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] Once relevant metrics have been chosen, the code on which the metrics will be applied should be available and relevant to the problem, either by reflecting the behavior of real-world application, or by being relevant to the particular problem the algorithm wants to address.
[src:static-single-assignment/register-allocation] The more recent articles about register allocation uses especially the Dacapo benchmark suite.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In compiler design, **static single assignment form** (often abbreviated as **SSA form** or simply **SSA**) is a type of intermediate representation (IR) where each variable is assigned exactly once.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] SSA is used in most high-quality optimizing compilers for imperative languages, including LLVM, the GNU Compiler Collection, and many commercial compilers.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] There are efficient algorithms for converting programs into SSA form.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] To convert to SSA, existing variables in the original IR are split into versions, new variables typically indicated by the original name with a subscript, so that every definition gets its own version.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Additional statements that assign to new versions of variables may also need to be introduced at the join point of two control flow paths.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Converting from SSA form to machine code is also efficient.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] SSA makes numerous analyses needed for optimizations easier to perform, such as determining use-define chains, because when looking at a use of a variable there is only one place where that variable may have received a value.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Most optimizations can be adapted to preserve SSA form, so that one optimization can be performed after another with no additional analysis.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] The SSA based optimizations are usually more efficient and more powerful than their non-SSA form prior equivalents.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In functional language compilers, such as those for Scheme and ML, continuation-passing style (CPS) is generally used.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] SSA is formally equivalent to a well-behaved subset of CPS excluding non-local control flow, so optimizations and transformations formulated in terms of one generally apply to the other.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Using CPS as the intermediate representation is more natural for higher-order functions and interprocedural analysis.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] CPS also easily encodes call/cc, whereas SSA does not.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] SSA was developed in the 1980s by several researchers at IBM.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Kenneth Zadeck, a key member of the team, moved to Brown University as development continued.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A 1986 paper introduced birthpoints, identity assignments, and variable renaming such that variables had a single static assignment.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A subsequent 1987 paper by Jeanne Ferrante and Ronald Cytron proved that the renaming done in the previous paper removes all false dependencies for scalars.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Wegman, and Kenneth Zadeck replaced the identity assignments with Φ-functions, introduced the name "static single-assignment form", and demonstrated a now-common SSA optimization.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] The name Φ-function was chosen by Rosen to be a more publishable version of "phony function".
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Alpern, Wegman, and Zadeck presented another optimization, but using the name "static single assignment".
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Finally, in 1989, Rosen, Wegman, Zadeck, Cytron, and Ferrante found an efficient means of converting programs to SSA form.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] The primary usefulness of SSA comes from how it simultaneously simplifies and improves the results of a variety of compiler optimizations, by simplifying the properties of variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Humans can see that the first assignment is not necessary, and that the value of `y` being used in the third line comes from the second assignment of `y`.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A program would have to perform reaching definition analysis to determine this.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Converting ordinary code into SSA form is primarily a matter of replacing the target of each assignment with a new variable, and replacing each use of a variable with the "version" of the variable reaching that point.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Changing the name on the left hand side of "x $\leftarrow$ x - 3" and changing the following uses of *x* to that new name would leave the program unaltered.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] This can be exploited in SSA by creating two new variables: *x*1 and *x*2, each of which is assigned only once.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] It is clear which definition each use is referring to, except for one case: both uses of *y* in the bottom block could be referring to either *y*1 or *y*2, depending on which path the control flow took.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] To resolve this, a special statement is inserted in the last block, called a *Φ (Phi) function*.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] This statement will generate a new definition of *y* called *y*3 by "choosing" either *y*1 or *y*2, depending on the control flow in the past.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Now, the last block can simply use *y*3, and the correct value will be obtained either way.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A Φ function for *x* is not needed: only one version of *x*, namely *x*2 is reaching this place, so there is no problem (in other words, Φ(*x*2,*x*2)=*x*2).
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Given an arbitrary control-flow graph, it can be difficult to tell where to insert Φ functions, and for which variables.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] This general question has an efficient solution that can be computed using a concept called *dominance frontiers* (see below).
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Φ functions are not implemented as machine operations on most machines.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A compiler can implement a Φ function by inserting "move" operations at the end of every predecessor block.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In the example above, the compiler might insert a move from *y*1 to *y*3 at the end of the middle-left block and a move from *y*2 to *y*3 at the end of the middle-right block.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] These move operations might not end up in the final code based on the compiler's register allocation procedure.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] However, this approach may not work when simultaneous operations are speculatively producing inputs to a Φ function, as can happen on wide-issue machines.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Typically, a wide-issue machine has a selection instruction used in such situations by the compiler to implement the Φ function.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In a control-flow graph, a node A is said to **strictly dominate** a different node B if it is impossible to reach B without passing through A first.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In other words, if node B is reached, then it can be assumed that A has run.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A is said to *dominate* B (or B to *be dominated by* A) if either A strictly dominates B or A = B.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A node which transfers control to a node A is called an **immediate predecessor** of A.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] The **dominance frontier** of node A is the set of nodes B where A *does not* strictly dominate B, but does dominate some immediate predecessor of B.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] These are the points at which multiple control paths merge back together into a single path.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Node 1 strictly dominates 2, 3, and 4 and the immediate predecessors of node 4 are nodes 2 and 3.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Dominance frontiers define the points at which Φ functions are needed.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In the above example, when control is passed to node 4, the definition of `result` used depends on whether control was passed from node 2 or 3. Φ functions are not needed for variables defined in a dominator, as there is only one possible definition that can apply.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] There is an efficient algorithm for finding dominance frontiers of each node.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] This algorithm was originally described in "Efficiently Computing Static Single Assignment Form and the Control Graph" by Ron Cytron, Jeanne Ferrante, et al. in 1991.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In the code above, `idom(b)` is the **immediate dominator** of b, the unique node that strictly dominates b but does not strictly dominate any other node that strictly dominates b.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] "Minimal" SSA inserts the minimal number of Φ functions required to ensure that each name is assigned a value exactly once and that each reference (use) of a name in the original program can still refer to a unique name.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] However, some of these Φ functions could be *dead*.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] For this reason, minimal SSA does not necessarily produce the fewest Φ functions that are needed by a specific procedure.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] For some types of analysis, these Φ functions are superfluous and can cause the analysis to run less efficiently.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Pruned SSA form is based on a simple observation: Φ functions are only needed for variables that are "live" after the Φ function.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] (Here, "live" means that the value is used along some path that begins at the Φ function in question.) If a variable is not live, the result of the Φ function cannot be used and the assignment by the Φ function is dead.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Construction of pruned SSA form uses live-variable information in the Φ function insertion phase to decide whether a given Φ function is needed.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] If the original variable name isn't live at the Φ function insertion point, the Φ function isn't inserted.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Another possibility is to treat pruning as a dead-code elimination problem.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Then, a Φ function is live only if any use in the input program will be rewritten to it, or if it will be used as an argument in another Φ function.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] When entering SSA form, each use is rewritten to the nearest definition that dominates it.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] A Φ function will then be considered live as long as it is the nearest definition that dominates at least one use, or at least one argument of a live Φ.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Semi-pruned SSA form is an attempt to reduce the number of Φ functions without incurring the relatively high cost of computing live-variable information.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] It is based on the following observation: if a variable is never live upon entry into a basic block, it never needs a Φ function.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] During SSA construction, Φ functions for any "block-local" variables are omitted.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Computing the set of block-local variables is a simpler and faster procedure than full live-variable analysis, making semi-pruned SSA form more efficient to compute than pruned SSA form.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] On the other hand, semi-pruned SSA form will contain more Φ functions.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Block arguments are an alternative to Φ functions that is representationally identical but in practice can be more convenient during optimization.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Blocks are named and take a list of block arguments, notated as function parameters.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] When calling a block the block arguments are bound to specified values.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] MLton, Swift SIL, and MLIR use block arguments.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Block arguments make the connection to continuation-passing style (CPS) more apparent: basic blocks are functions, function variables are block arguments (Φ functions).
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] SSA form is not normally used for direct execution (although it is possible to interpret SSA), and it is frequently used "on top of" another IR with which it remains in direct correspondence.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] This can be accomplished by "constructing" SSA as a set of functions that map between parts of the existing IR (basic blocks, instructions, operands, *etc.*) and its SSA counterpart.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] When the SSA form is no longer needed, these mapping functions may be discarded, leaving only the now-optimized IR.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Performing optimizations on SSA form usually leads to entangled SSA-Webs, meaning there are Φ instructions whose operands do not all have the same root operand.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] In such cases color-out algorithms are used to come out of SSA.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Naive algorithms introduce a copy along each predecessor path that caused a source of different root symbol to be put in Φ than the destination of Φ.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] There are multiple algorithms for coming out of SSA with fewer copies, most use interference graphs or some approximation of it to do copy coalescing.
[src:static-single-assignment/static-single-assignment-form] Extensions to SSA form can be divided into two categories.
